1
00:00:10,375 --> 00:00:12,291
Assault unit is approaching.

2
00:00:13,666 --> 00:00:16,250
Move! I want a clean intervention.

3
00:00:16,333 --> 00:00:18,625
They're armed and extremely dangerous.

4
00:00:19,583 --> 00:00:20,958
Let's go, fast!

5
00:00:21,041 --> 00:00:22,291
First floor, clear.

6
00:00:22,916 --> 00:00:25,208
I want every floor cleared. Let's go!

7
00:00:25,291 --> 00:00:27,083
Watch all the exits.

8
00:00:27,708 --> 00:00:28,916
Second floor, clear.

9
00:00:41,250 --> 00:00:42,250
Please…

10
00:00:46,916 --> 00:00:48,666
-Police!
-Let's go!

11
00:00:49,250 --> 00:00:51,875
-Hands up!
-Police!

12
00:00:51,958 --> 00:00:53,375
Colonel, are you okay?

13
00:00:54,500 --> 00:00:56,750
My wife.

14
00:00:57,458 --> 00:00:58,833
Let's go!

15
00:01:01,250 --> 00:01:02,083
Luis!

16
00:01:04,250 --> 00:01:05,125
No one's here.

17
00:01:05,208 --> 00:01:06,625
How long has it been?

18
00:01:07,500 --> 00:01:09,083
I don't know. A few minutes.

19
00:01:09,166 --> 00:01:11,000
It's Sierra. She's carrying a baby.

20
00:01:11,083 --> 00:01:12,625
No one has left the building.

21
00:01:12,708 --> 00:01:15,875
Check every apartment.
If nobody opens, break the door down.

22
00:01:15,958 --> 00:01:17,583
Set up a cage operation

23
00:01:17,666 --> 00:01:20,375
with a one-mile perimeter
no one can get out of.

24
00:01:20,458 --> 00:01:22,541
Bravo 41 calling all available units.

25
00:01:22,625 --> 00:01:25,916
Cage Operation, Chamberí district.
Limits, Valdebebas, and Canillas.

26
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:28,958
I repeat, Bravo 41
calling all available units.

27
00:01:31,208 --> 00:01:32,416
Listen, ma'am.

28
00:01:32,500 --> 00:01:35,166
Everything's going to be okay,
but you can't scream.

29
00:01:42,875 --> 00:01:44,166
Give me the baby.

30
00:01:47,291 --> 00:01:49,750
And my glasses. I need my glasses.

31
00:01:49,833 --> 00:01:50,958
Let's go, quick.

32
00:01:55,791 --> 00:01:57,291
-Open the door!
-Police!

33
00:02:08,708 --> 00:02:11,416
You're bleeding.
You're not going to go, are you?

34
00:02:11,500 --> 00:02:14,500
I have to go back.
This is the final stretch.

35
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:16,666
But I promise you one thing.

36
00:02:18,333 --> 00:02:19,833
This is my last stretch.

37
00:02:21,541 --> 00:02:24,583
Call in the army. Declare martial law.

38
00:02:24,666 --> 00:02:27,375
We're going to search the neighborhood
door to door.

39
00:02:37,833 --> 00:02:39,250
No, please--

40
00:02:40,125 --> 00:02:41,083
Calm down.

41
00:02:42,208 --> 00:02:43,416
Open the door now!

42
00:02:45,416 --> 00:02:47,208
Police! Open the door!

43
00:02:56,750 --> 00:02:57,708
Let's go!

44
00:02:57,791 --> 00:02:58,833
Police! Open the door!

45
00:03:08,166 --> 00:03:09,833
Police! Open the door!

46
00:03:15,125 --> 00:03:17,083
Police! Come on! Let's go!

47
00:03:26,291 --> 00:03:27,125
See you later.

48
00:03:29,500 --> 00:03:31,250
-What's going on?
-Move over.

49
00:03:41,916 --> 00:03:43,166
What the hell?

50
00:03:50,750 --> 00:03:51,750
Police!

51
00:03:51,833 --> 00:03:53,750
Open the door! Police!

52
00:03:58,625 --> 00:03:59,916
The baby.

53
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:01,375
The baby's asleep.

54
00:04:10,625 --> 00:04:12,291
Let's go!

55
00:04:23,833 --> 00:04:26,125
-The baby.
-The baby's fine.

56
00:04:34,583 --> 00:04:35,833
Good evening.

57
00:04:40,083 --> 00:04:40,958
Let's go!

58
00:04:42,208 --> 00:04:43,041
Clear!

59
00:04:45,208 --> 00:04:46,875
They escaped through the courtyard.

60
00:04:55,166 --> 00:04:56,791
-Go!
-Let's go!

61
00:05:05,625 --> 00:05:07,375
Everyone go to the courtyard!

62
00:05:09,208 --> 00:05:10,666
-Your glasses.
-What?

63
00:05:11,166 --> 00:05:12,958
Your sunglasses. It's dark out.

64
00:05:13,041 --> 00:05:14,750
So what? Who cares?

65
00:05:14,833 --> 00:05:16,583
-Take them off.
-Shut up.

66
00:05:21,208 --> 00:05:22,208
They're coming.

67
00:05:22,708 --> 00:05:25,291
-Shut up.
-They're coming.

68
00:05:26,666 --> 00:05:30,250
Calling all units.
They left through the restaurant.

69
00:05:30,333 --> 00:05:32,375
-Turn around!
-Legs apart!

70
00:05:35,500 --> 00:05:37,958
We'll get there faster
if we take the subway.

71
00:05:39,750 --> 00:05:42,083
Turn around! Hands against the wall!

72
00:05:48,708 --> 00:05:49,625
Professor?

73
00:06:10,541 --> 00:06:13,041
Professor, do you copy?

74
00:06:15,666 --> 00:06:17,125
Quiet, boys.

75
00:06:28,083 --> 00:06:30,041
-Professor?
-Professor?

76
00:06:34,333 --> 00:06:36,208
-Marseille to Benjamín.
-Copy.

77
00:06:36,291 --> 00:06:37,416
The Professor's gone.

78
00:06:38,458 --> 00:06:39,333
Come again?

79
00:06:39,416 --> 00:06:42,250
I think Alicia Sierra
kidnapped him, again.

80
00:06:42,833 --> 00:06:44,833
My men are here. What should we do?

81
00:06:44,916 --> 00:06:47,000
Do as the Professor asked. Take command.

82
00:06:47,083 --> 00:06:49,375
I'll take the three cars
to the stormwater tank.

83
00:06:49,458 --> 00:06:51,708
I have to tie up all loose ends.

84
00:07:08,958 --> 00:07:10,166
What?

85
00:07:12,375 --> 00:07:13,375
Let's go to 2B.

86
00:07:18,208 --> 00:07:19,083
Come on.

87
00:07:24,708 --> 00:07:25,583
There.

88
00:07:29,916 --> 00:07:30,916
No one's home.

89
00:07:47,625 --> 00:07:48,500
Come on.

90
00:08:14,541 --> 00:08:15,375
Clear.

91
00:08:21,708 --> 00:08:23,083
Fuck, it's a cat.

92
00:08:30,541 --> 00:08:33,625
"Plants, twice a week.
Cat, one bowl a day."

93
00:08:34,125 --> 00:08:35,291
"Thanks, Herminia."

94
00:08:36,375 --> 00:08:37,916
The plants were watered today.

95
00:08:38,416 --> 00:08:40,875
So Herminia won't be back until tomorrow.

96
00:08:41,833 --> 00:08:44,416
The government has declared martial law.

97
00:08:45,708 --> 00:08:47,666
We're here to protect you.

98
00:08:48,666 --> 00:08:49,583
Quick!

99
00:08:51,083 --> 00:08:52,833
Let's go!

100
00:08:52,916 --> 00:08:55,375
This is starting to look like
the Warsaw ghetto.

101
00:08:57,291 --> 00:08:59,125
They're going to search every house.

102
00:10:14,041 --> 00:10:15,375
Come here.

103
00:10:17,083 --> 00:10:20,291
Is it possible my illness
is starting to get to you?

104
00:10:20,375 --> 00:10:21,333
It is, isn't it?

105
00:10:21,833 --> 00:10:22,666
No.

106
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:25,916
-No.
-Yes.

107
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:31,250
It's just that I'm moved
by this wonderful plan with the gold.

108
00:10:31,750 --> 00:10:33,750
There are a few details I still…

109
00:10:35,791 --> 00:10:37,416
-Go on.
-Yeah.

110
00:10:38,208 --> 00:10:40,875
-How to get the gold out, for instance.
-Grit.

111
00:10:40,958 --> 00:10:44,875
We're going to turn
90 tons of gold into rice.

112
00:10:44,958 --> 00:10:47,666
And then, jet propulsion.

113
00:10:47,750 --> 00:10:51,000
We'll get it out of the building
using a pressure pump.

114
00:10:51,083 --> 00:10:52,500
-With a pump?
-Yes.

115
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:54,083
Through the pipes?

116
00:10:55,250 --> 00:10:57,333
Is there a pressure pump in the bank?

117
00:10:57,416 --> 00:10:58,500
-Of course not.
-Right.

118
00:10:58,583 --> 00:11:00,583
We had to go to Norway to get one.

119
00:11:01,166 --> 00:11:03,875
From an oil platform.
What do you think about that?

120
00:11:05,083 --> 00:11:08,541
There was also one in Saudi Arabia,
but I was too lazy to go that far.

121
00:11:08,625 --> 00:11:09,583
Of course.

122
00:11:09,666 --> 00:11:10,791
What matters, Sergio,

123
00:11:10,875 --> 00:11:15,208
is that we're going to have a geyser
of golden light flowing through the pipes.

124
00:11:15,291 --> 00:11:16,791
There's no margin for error.

125
00:11:17,291 --> 00:11:20,416
Andrés, the whole plan
is a margin for error.

126
00:11:20,500 --> 00:11:24,041
How old are those pipes?
Fifty, 70 years old?

127
00:11:28,250 --> 00:11:29,291
A hundred.

128
00:11:29,375 --> 00:11:33,291
Do you think they were designed to support
the flow of gold under pressure?

129
00:11:33,375 --> 00:11:34,833
They'll hold!

130
00:11:36,166 --> 00:11:38,750
Where will the gold be delivered?
To a sewer?

131
00:11:38,833 --> 00:11:39,666
No!

132
00:11:41,291 --> 00:11:44,291
I love this.
In the biggest stormwater tank in Europe.

133
00:11:45,541 --> 00:11:47,791
In a stormwater tank? What if it rains?

134
00:11:48,500 --> 00:11:51,416
What if it starts pouring that day?
It would collapse!

135
00:11:51,500 --> 00:11:55,416
You can kiss your plan and life goodbye,
simply because it rained.

136
00:11:55,500 --> 00:11:57,125
No, it's not science, it's…

137
00:11:57,916 --> 00:11:58,875
wishful thinking.

138
00:11:58,958 --> 00:12:00,583
It's optimistic science!

139
00:12:00,666 --> 00:12:02,083
What are you talking about?

140
00:12:02,166 --> 00:12:04,083
-It's hopeful science.
-Who's talking?

141
00:12:04,166 --> 00:12:07,458
The brain of someone planning a heist
or the brain of a child?

142
00:12:08,041 --> 00:12:09,041
A child's.

143
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:13,166
I'm proud of that.

144
00:12:13,750 --> 00:12:16,458
-I'm Peter Pan himself.
-I see.

145
00:12:16,541 --> 00:12:19,500
No one's going to make me lose hope,
not you or anyone else.

146
00:12:19,583 --> 00:12:23,750
Because only then,
through willful immaturity,

147
00:12:24,333 --> 00:12:26,416
can one achieve great things.

148
00:12:26,500 --> 00:12:28,375
The sort of things that other,

149
00:12:28,458 --> 00:12:31,250
mature people, serious people,
can never achieve.

150
00:12:31,333 --> 00:12:34,541
They can't even imagine it
because they're all so very sensible!

151
00:12:37,875 --> 00:12:43,125
And for those of us who think,
is there anything we can hold onto?

152
00:12:44,083 --> 00:12:45,291
Anything?

153
00:12:45,375 --> 00:12:47,625
Because I'd love to check the facts.

154
00:12:47,708 --> 00:12:52,875
Martín has it all figured out.
Every last detail.

155
00:12:54,375 --> 00:12:57,166
And he'd be delighted
to share it with to you.

156
00:13:00,500 --> 00:13:02,041
Come on, guys, let's go.

157
00:13:03,083 --> 00:13:05,375
The waterwheel goes last, okay Darko?

158
00:13:05,458 --> 00:13:07,041
The waterwheel goes last.

159
00:13:08,833 --> 00:13:10,041
Benjamín, are you there?

160
00:13:11,333 --> 00:13:13,291
Yes, Miss Lisbon.

161
00:13:19,291 --> 00:13:21,500
The Professor has disappeared.

162
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:27,500
Wait a minute.

163
00:13:27,583 --> 00:13:30,000
What do you mean
"the Professor has disappeared"?

164
00:13:30,083 --> 00:13:31,916
Is he in the Bermuda Triangle?

165
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:34,208
How would I know? I don't know.

166
00:13:35,958 --> 00:13:36,791
Fuck…

167
00:13:36,875 --> 00:13:41,083
But we have to make a decision right now.
What should we do with the gold?

168
00:13:42,166 --> 00:13:44,708
I'm sorry, are you planning a referendum?

169
00:13:45,666 --> 00:13:48,333
Because I don't give a shit
about democracy.

170
00:13:51,333 --> 00:13:52,666
We're getting the gold out.

171
00:13:53,541 --> 00:13:55,041
There's no room for debate.

172
00:13:55,125 --> 00:13:57,750
If you let them debate,
they'll draw their weapons.

173
00:13:57,833 --> 00:14:01,083
Let me draw mine first.
Don't fuck with me, we know each other.

174
00:14:01,166 --> 00:14:04,041
The police might be
at the gold's exit point.

175
00:14:05,791 --> 00:14:10,541
The police aren't in the stormwater tank.
The plan is still on, understood?

176
00:14:10,625 --> 00:14:15,083
If that were the case, we'd be committing
the stupidest robbery in the world.

177
00:14:15,166 --> 00:14:17,833
Melting 90 tons of gold
to hand it over to the police.

178
00:14:17,916 --> 00:14:20,625
I said the police aren't
at the stormwater tank.

179
00:14:20,708 --> 00:14:24,208
The gold is worth nothing to us here.
Do you get it, sweetie?

180
00:14:24,291 --> 00:14:26,083
We're holding the gold hostage.

181
00:14:26,583 --> 00:14:27,791
Great.

182
00:14:28,291 --> 00:14:31,208
We take the hostage,
offer it to Tamayo, and negotiate.

183
00:14:31,291 --> 00:14:33,875
Is that your master plan?
Are you the genius?

184
00:14:36,500 --> 00:14:38,500
Yes, honey, I'm a fucking genius,

185
00:14:38,583 --> 00:14:42,000
and I have the machinery
down there to prove it, don't worry.

186
00:14:42,083 --> 00:14:43,708
Is that all you care about?

187
00:14:43,791 --> 00:14:46,000
Proving that your wonderful plan works?

188
00:14:46,083 --> 00:14:48,083
Yes, but also about saving your lives.

189
00:14:48,166 --> 00:14:51,000
We're going to do that
by getting the gold out of here.

190
00:14:52,333 --> 00:14:53,500
Palermo is right.

191
00:14:54,791 --> 00:14:56,541
There are only two people out there

192
00:14:56,625 --> 00:14:59,458
who can tell them
how we're getting the gold out.

193
00:14:59,541 --> 00:15:03,416
The Professor, and he's not going to tell,
and Alicia Sierra.

194
00:15:03,500 --> 00:15:06,875
She'll use that information
to negotiate and get off the hook.

195
00:15:08,166 --> 00:15:09,875
And I assure you

196
00:15:09,958 --> 00:15:13,041
that negotiating
with Intelligence will be tough.

197
00:15:13,125 --> 00:15:14,666
It'll take hours.

198
00:15:14,750 --> 00:15:18,416
We'll have time to get the gold out.
That's what we're going to do.

199
00:15:21,750 --> 00:15:23,958
This woman has sex appeal and balls.

200
00:15:25,125 --> 00:15:27,291
We're going to get the gold out of here!

201
00:15:28,833 --> 00:15:30,291
We're going to get it out.

202
00:15:30,375 --> 00:15:32,958
Just then,
Palermo recovered his enthusiasm.

203
00:15:33,708 --> 00:15:35,958
The last time he had
that sparkle in his eyes

204
00:15:36,041 --> 00:15:37,583
was five years ago,

205
00:15:38,625 --> 00:15:41,083
when someone woke him up
in the middle of the night.

206
00:15:42,750 --> 00:15:44,500
I told him the plan.

207
00:15:49,583 --> 00:15:51,000
What did he say?

208
00:15:51,625 --> 00:15:53,291
Let's say he thought it was

209
00:15:54,500 --> 00:15:56,125
a real wonder.

210
00:15:58,083 --> 00:15:59,958
Let me be precise.

211
00:16:01,750 --> 00:16:04,541
He said it's the most beautiful thing
he's ever heard.

212
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:10,083
Don't fuck with me. Are you serious?

213
00:16:11,125 --> 00:16:12,041
Martín,

214
00:16:12,625 --> 00:16:14,250
I told him the gist of it.

215
00:16:14,333 --> 00:16:17,416
He wants you to explain
all the technical details.

216
00:16:18,166 --> 00:16:20,916
So, it's your turn.

217
00:16:21,708 --> 00:16:22,916
No shit.

218
00:16:23,541 --> 00:16:25,166
Oh my God, I can't believe it.

219
00:16:27,500 --> 00:16:28,416
Let's see.

220
00:16:29,208 --> 00:16:32,583
Houndstooth? Tartan?
Something that exudes intellect.

221
00:16:32,666 --> 00:16:35,833
I'd say that's a bit sophisticated
for 3:00 a.m.

222
00:16:35,916 --> 00:16:39,750
A touch of genius would be good,
but go for something casual.

223
00:16:42,958 --> 00:16:46,083
For Palermo and Berlin,
"maturity" meant the same thing,

224
00:16:46,166 --> 00:16:48,291
the end of hopes and dreams,

225
00:16:48,375 --> 00:16:51,625
and starting to approach life
with a certain bitter awareness.

226
00:16:52,125 --> 00:16:56,750
After all, maturing, like growing old,
consists of gradually discarding dreams.

227
00:17:05,666 --> 00:17:07,166
Bogotá, get in the water!

228
00:17:09,083 --> 00:17:10,458
-Bogotá!
-What?

229
00:17:10,541 --> 00:17:11,583
Get in the water!

230
00:17:14,625 --> 00:17:19,041
You didn't have to get him out of bed now.
We could have done it tomorrow morning.

231
00:17:19,125 --> 00:17:21,583
It's a great privilege for me to be here.

232
00:17:21,666 --> 00:17:24,833
What do your curiosity
and sharp intellect require?

233
00:17:24,916 --> 00:17:25,958
Tell me.

234
00:17:26,708 --> 00:17:29,125
Let's say we've turned
the 90 tons into grit.

235
00:17:29,208 --> 00:17:30,416
-Yes?
-Now what?

236
00:17:31,833 --> 00:17:36,083
Now we put the diver back in the water,
only, this time, with two hoses.

237
00:17:39,125 --> 00:17:42,666
Having completely ransacked the vault
like King Tut's tomb,

238
00:17:42,750 --> 00:17:44,750
the diver will make the key connection.

239
00:17:44,833 --> 00:17:47,041
That will allow us
to move the gold off-site.

240
00:17:47,125 --> 00:17:49,041
-How?
-We have the vault, right?

241
00:17:49,125 --> 00:17:52,458
There's 3,170 gallons of water.
That will be our driving force.

242
00:17:54,166 --> 00:17:57,416
Through this black pipe,
the water goes into this pump,

243
00:17:57,500 --> 00:17:59,083
where it'll mix with the gold.

244
00:17:59,166 --> 00:18:03,333
And the 90 tons of grit will flow
through this red hose,

245
00:18:03,416 --> 00:18:07,000
smoothly, towards the drainage system.

246
00:18:07,500 --> 00:18:09,583
-Diameter of the hose?
-Five inches.

247
00:18:09,666 --> 00:18:13,125
You can't get enough pressure
to get the gold out with that hose.

248
00:18:13,208 --> 00:18:14,125
Exactly.

249
00:18:15,166 --> 00:18:19,500
Because, for now, the gold will be
sleeping peacefully in the drainpipes.

250
00:18:19,583 --> 00:18:21,041
The real pressure

251
00:18:23,166 --> 00:18:24,791
will come a little later.

252
00:18:25,791 --> 00:18:28,000
We will proceed to open every door.

253
00:18:28,583 --> 00:18:31,500
We are prepared to use force,
and will not allow…

254
00:18:31,583 --> 00:18:33,041
Delta Unit entering.

255
00:18:36,458 --> 00:18:37,375
What are you doing?

256
00:18:39,791 --> 00:18:41,041
We're going to hide.

257
00:18:43,166 --> 00:18:44,625
Let's go, move it!

258
00:18:44,708 --> 00:18:46,375
Let's go!

