00:43:01,875 --> 00:43:03,375
Keep your mouth shut.

522
00:43:04,125 --> 00:43:05,125
Hey, look at me.

523
00:43:06,541 --> 00:43:08,083
Because once you confess,

524
00:43:08,166 --> 00:43:11,583
that's written in stone,
it's like confessing to the police.

525
00:43:12,208 --> 00:43:13,916
And then, my friend,

526
00:43:15,541 --> 00:43:17,291
there's no way to fix things.

527
00:43:30,291 --> 00:43:31,166
The baby.

528
00:43:39,958 --> 00:43:40,791
Honey.

529
00:44:02,166 --> 00:44:03,125
Sergio.

530
00:44:10,083 --> 00:44:12,333
-What are you doing?
-I found a cell phone.

531
00:44:12,416 --> 00:44:14,208
It's charging. It's at two bars.

532
00:44:14,875 --> 00:44:17,083
It's a little old, but it'll work.

533
00:44:27,500 --> 00:44:29,750
INCOMING CALL

534
00:44:44,041 --> 00:44:45,125
Hello?

535
00:44:46,375 --> 00:44:48,833
-Who are you?
-I'm Shakir.

536
00:44:48,916 --> 00:44:51,958
-I support the Professor from Asia.
-Holy moly.

537
00:44:52,583 --> 00:44:53,750
I'm Benjamín.

538
00:44:53,833 --> 00:44:54,958
I'll put you through.

539
00:44:55,041 --> 00:44:55,958
Yes, of course.

540
00:45:02,083 --> 00:45:03,458
-Professor.
-Listen.

541
00:45:03,541 --> 00:45:05,833
We're out of time. Call the Serbians.

542
00:45:05,916 --> 00:45:07,041
They're here.

543
00:45:07,625 --> 00:45:11,000
I made them come
to guard the outer perimeter.

544
00:45:11,083 --> 00:45:12,916
That's great, Benjamín.

545
00:45:13,000 --> 00:45:15,583
You put me in charge.
I'm taking things as they come.

546
00:45:15,666 --> 00:45:16,916
I'm doing the best I can.

547
00:45:17,625 --> 00:45:20,125
In that case, you have a mission now.

548
00:45:24,916 --> 00:45:26,166
Marseille, let's go.

549
00:45:26,750 --> 00:45:29,041
We have a mission. Tell the Serbians.

550
00:45:29,125 --> 00:45:31,083
Boris, with us. Get the circular saws,

551
00:45:31,166 --> 00:45:34,875
the thermal lances,
the welding machine, mops, and a few guns.

552
00:45:36,458 --> 00:45:40,666
And the rest of you, keep making ingots
like there's no tomorrow!

553
00:45:40,750 --> 00:45:42,458
Let's go!

554
00:46:04,291 --> 00:46:05,541
Get out, and get changed.

555
00:46:35,750 --> 00:46:38,541
Deep down,
Berlin and the Professor were a lot alike.

556
00:46:38,625 --> 00:46:41,875
They both designed plans
based on one powerful concept…

557
00:46:44,083 --> 00:46:44,916
Thrill.

558
00:46:45,000 --> 00:46:45,833
Stop right there.

559
00:46:45,916 --> 00:46:49,166
For the Professor, "thrill" meant
disguising the extraordinary

560
00:46:49,250 --> 00:46:51,291
as something completely ordinary.

561
00:46:52,625 --> 00:46:54,000
A garbage truck.

562
00:46:58,541 --> 00:47:02,250
For Berlin, "thrill" meant
believing the impossible was possible.

563
00:47:03,041 --> 00:47:04,750
And although he didn't think so,

564
00:47:04,833 --> 00:47:07,250
in that way,
the Professor was like his brother.

565
00:47:07,791 --> 00:47:10,333
Because only with that childlike fantasy

566
00:47:11,041 --> 00:47:13,875
can one play hide-and-seek
on a street guarded by soldiers.

567
00:47:13,958 --> 00:47:17,958
A garbage truck is asking for permission
to enter at control point 1-2-6.

568
00:47:21,958 --> 00:47:26,291
Berlin's Peter Pan pride radiated
over the most important escape of all…

569
00:47:26,875 --> 00:47:27,791
Crossing clear.

570
00:47:27,875 --> 00:47:31,166
…an all-or-nothing gamble
in a magical moment.

571
00:47:32,375 --> 00:47:36,000
Like when they discovered
the heist was technically possible.

572
00:47:36,541 --> 00:47:40,333
It was as if they knew how to get to Mars,
but not how to return.

573
00:47:42,000 --> 00:47:45,583
But they celebrated enthusiastically,
as only children can.

574
00:48:03,458 --> 00:48:05,166
One, two, three…

575
00:48:05,750 --> 00:48:06,875
hide-and-seek.

576
00:48:08,000 --> 00:48:09,583
That's how it happened.

577
00:48:09,666 --> 00:48:11,750
In an instant of complete normalcy.

578
00:48:14,833 --> 00:48:17,333
The truck swallowed the garbage.

579
00:48:18,416 --> 00:48:20,041
But it was much more than that.

580
00:48:22,666 --> 00:48:23,500
Professor.

581
00:48:23,583 --> 00:48:27,000
It was putting the heist's brain
back in charge of the game,

582
00:48:27,500 --> 00:48:29,375
with a new brain by his side.

583
00:48:30,000 --> 00:48:31,000
And more importantly…

584
00:48:35,625 --> 00:48:36,916
…the Professor realized

585
00:48:37,000 --> 00:48:40,000
the enthusiasm for the heist
his brother had infected him with

586
00:48:40,500 --> 00:48:43,041
had now infected his entire team.

587
00:48:44,083 --> 00:48:48,416
That while he had been in technical KO,
lying on the canvas…

588
00:48:48,500 --> 00:48:49,958
You'll see, Professor.

589
00:48:50,041 --> 00:48:53,208
-We did the best we could.
-That's good.

590
00:48:53,291 --> 00:48:55,291
…the machinery had kept running.

591
00:48:56,791 --> 00:48:58,333
The gold was outside,

592
00:48:59,166 --> 00:49:02,000
and the exterior foundry
was in full swing.

593
00:49:03,583 --> 00:49:05,875
The dream was more alive than ever.

594
00:49:29,916 --> 00:49:30,750
They did it.

595
00:49:39,916 --> 00:49:40,958
They did it.

596
00:49:41,958 --> 00:49:43,791
Palermo, they did it.

597
00:49:44,291 --> 00:49:46,791
There's a foundry in the stormwater tank.

598
00:49:47,291 --> 00:49:49,500
Of course it's out, brother!

599
00:49:49,583 --> 00:49:51,958
Isn't it the most beautiful thing
you've ever seen?

600
00:49:52,041 --> 00:49:53,416
The gold is coming out.

601
00:50:01,583 --> 00:50:03,000
The gold is coming out!

602
00:50:07,833 --> 00:50:09,208
This one's for you, Andrés.

603
00:50:09,291 --> 00:50:13,125
With a pump this powerful,
they'll hear the suction or the pumping.

604
00:50:13,208 --> 00:50:16,416
It'll be easy for them
to figure out we're using the pipes.

605
00:50:19,458 --> 00:50:21,250
Why won't they be waiting for us?

606
00:50:21,833 --> 00:50:26,041
That's an excellent question, Sergio,
but we do have the answer.

607
00:50:26,125 --> 00:50:29,333
And the answer is the difference
between a white-collar thief

608
00:50:29,416 --> 00:50:30,708
and us.

609
00:50:30,791 --> 00:50:33,541
The difference between
being good and being a genius.

610
00:50:33,625 --> 00:50:35,875
And we aspire to genius.

611
00:52:05,416 --> 00:52:08,833
Subtitle translation by: Molly Yurick
